<subSubSection id="303206C0F19BC28C0C49D8814DF78280" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="diagnostic description">
<paragraph id="BCA329A4B05B4D2E3134C198A84319E5" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Diagnostic description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF07E5254EE3F5619B5B17C8725488C3" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Mandible lacinia mobilis a stemmed, distally expanded, irregularly cusped blade; palp article 2 broadened. 
<emphasis id="B2438D9D20706526F9C5546C8EAA0654" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Maxilla 2</emphasis>
inner plate longer than outer plate; 
<emphasis id="434E33ECEB0FCC94E1670F83C5C41D4E" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">outer plate with extremely long distally barbed slender setae</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="AAAE05EDA0A234AC2609B09415E61560" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Gnathopod 1 coxa margins diverging distally</emphasis>
. Pereopod 5 coxa slightly wider than long; basis greatly expanded posteriorly.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="52533C329DAD203DBE74D1D0964CB892" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="A19F11C10BE88DB816A594CD2A0B9AEF" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0D7D51E604DA2E007B32EB9FE0E5A03B" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Western Atlantic. Mediterranean Sea. Japan. Australia.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="96B8BF5996FC4DA5D91AC4168ED078B1" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="150DF752DE2D7F10659F166FD4F332F9" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="49A27A45F6728D84E1F413C7915ACED9" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Found in shallow warm seas. A scavenger, also found in dead spatangoid tests.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="97D63359AE46A21116E514026CA5F15A" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="6FA52EE183FECCC5D4A76E1D076E7859" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E8FC2F65A7FF55C83B8918FD1B38B0B8" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Previously, the setal fringe on the distal margins of the coxae from gnathopod 1 to pereopod 4 was considered to be a diagnostic character of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="44B6720A0440019CF6D36B86D21FA537" authorityName="Chevreux" authorityYear="1911" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Aroui" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aroui" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="CBCC77FB73D0532D523CCE3BBD085FBB" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Aroui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Here we exclude that character from the diagnosis of the genus, as the setal fringe is absent in 
<taxonomicName id="C1EBDC8A08ED356D758302EEC3FF7175" authorityName="Kilgallen &amp; Lowry" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Takekawa &amp; Ishimaru" baseAuthorityYear="2000" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Aroui" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aroui onagawae" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="onagawae">
<emphasis id="8D1B4B653B7F98F33A811AD0DE0D2FE0" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Aroui onagawae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Takekawa &amp; Ishimaru, 2000), comb. n. Instead, we consider the unusual long, distally barbed setae on the outer plate of maxilla 2 to be an autapomorphy that distinguishes 
<taxonomicName id="8B10C97F2F23A2365B62083490FBD4D8" authorityName="Chevreux" authorityYear="1911" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Aroui" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aroui" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6658C037A6CE7B94EE4E1DA84D8C4551" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Aroui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from all other genera in the 
<taxonomicName id="FD6B6114F5FDB4E543A1D448FF2BC7B5" authorityName="Lowry &amp; Stoddart" authorityYear="1997" family="Scopelocheiridae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" rank="family">Scopelocheiridae</taxonomicName>
. See 
<taxonomicName id="4FF757B9C8CE921C0E8BC59373B8C4F8" authorityName="Kilgallen &amp; Lowry" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Takekawa &amp; Ishimaru" baseAuthorityYear="2000" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Aroui" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aroui onagawae" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="onagawae">
<emphasis id="F97F2C4F207762C770163E96F0F63363" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Aroui onagawae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, below, for further discussion.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
